## Diagnosis

The proxy middleware is almost certainly defined in `middleware.ts` (or `middleware.js`) at the project root, and its `matcher` config or internal routing logic is no longer intercepting `/api/internal/*` requests. In Next.js 16, the middleware execution model and matcher semantics changed in two important ways that silently break previously working auth proxies.

---

## Root cause — AP-072: Middleware Matcher Specificity Collapse

Next.js 16 (built on React 19 + stricter edge runtime contracts) tightened how the `matcher` array is evaluated:

1. **Glob syntax changed** — The `/:path*` wildcard now behaves differently from `/api/internal/:path*`. Patterns that previously matched greedily may now require explicit segment anchoring.
2. **`missing` / `has` conditions are evaluated before `matcher`** — If you use conditional logic inside the middleware body to decide whether to proxy, the runtime may short-circuit before your code runs.
3. **`proxy.ts` as a separate file is never auto-invoked** — Next.js only executes the default export of `middleware.ts`. A `proxy.ts` file that isn't explicitly imported and called from `middleware.ts` is silently dead code.

The most common manifestation: `proxy.ts` was working because it was imported inside `middleware.ts`, but an upgrade to `next.config.ts` or a dependency update tree-shook or reorganised that import.

---

## Fix

### 1. Verify `middleware.ts` is actually calling `proxy.ts`

```ts
// middleware.ts  (project root — NOT inside /app or /pages)
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import { applyInternalProxy } from './lib/proxy';   // ← must be explicit

export async function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  return applyInternalProxy(request);
}

export const config = {
  matcher: ['/api/internal/:path*'],   // ← see step 2
};
```

If this import is missing, proxy.ts is never executed — full stop.

---

### 2. Fix the matcher pattern for Next.js 16

```ts
// ✅ Next.js 16 — correct
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    /*
     * Explicit segment wildcard. The leading slash and :path*
     * must appear together; do NOT use a bare glob like
     * '/api/internal/**' — that syntax was deprecated.
     */
    '/api/internal/:path*',
  ],
};
```

```ts
// ❌ Patterns that worked in Next.js 15 but silently fail in 16
matcher: ['/api/internal/(.*)']   // RegExp-style string — no longer supported
matcher: ['/api/internal/**']     // Glob double-star — removed
matcher: [{ source: '/api/internal/:path*', missing: [...] }]  
// ↑ 'missing' blocks execution when the condition is not met,
//   which can invert your intent
```

---

### 3. Harden `proxy.ts` itself

```ts
// lib/proxy.ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';

const INTERNAL_API_PREFIX = '/api/internal';
const UPSTREAM = process.env.INTERNAL_API_UPSTREAM ?? '';  // e.g. https://api.yilangao.com

export async function applyInternalProxy(
  request: NextRequest,
): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const { pathname } = request.nextUrl;

  // Guard: only act on our prefix (defence-in-depth even if matcher is wrong)
  if (!pathname.startsWith(INTERNAL_API_PREFIX)) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // ── Auth check ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  const token = request.cookies.get('session')?.value
    ?? request.headers.get('authorization')?.replace('Bearer ', '');

  if (!token || !(await isValidToken(token))) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 401 });
  }

  // ── Proxy rewrite ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
  if (!UPSTREAM) {
    // Local route handlers — just forward with an auth header the
    // route handler can trust (internal network only)
    const headers = new Headers(request.headers);
    headers.set('x-internal-auth', process.env.INTERNAL_SECRET ?? '');
    return NextResponse.next({ request: { headers } });
  }

  // External upstream rewrite
  const upstreamUrl = new URL(
    pathname.replace(INTERNAL_API_PREFIX, '') + request.nextUrl.search,
    UPSTREAM,
  );

  return NextResponse.rewrite(upstreamUrl, {
    request: {
      headers: new Headers({
        ...Object.fromEntries(request.headers),
        'x-forwarded-host': request.nextUrl.host,
      }),
    },
  });
}

async function isValidToken(token: string): Promise<boolean> {
  // Replace with your Payload CMS session verification
  const res = await fetch(`${process.env.PAYLOAD_URL}/api/users/me`, {
    headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` },
    // next: { revalidate: 0 } — avoid caching auth checks
  });
  return res.ok;
}
```

---

### 4. Confirm middleware file placement

```
project-root/
├── middleware.ts          ← MUST be here (App Router)
├── lib/
│   └── proxy.ts
├── app/
│   └── api/
│       └── internal/
│           └── [...slug]/
│               └── route.ts
```

`middleware.ts` at any other depth (e.g. `app/middleware.ts`) is **not** picked up by Next.js 16.

---

### 5. Smoke-test the matcher before deploying

```ts
// scripts/test-matcher.ts  (run with: npx ts-node scripts/test-matcher.ts)
// Next.js exports a testable path-to-regexp instance you can validate locally
const paths = [
  '/api/internal/users',
  '/api/internal/users/123',
  '/api/internal/',
  '/api/public/users',       // must NOT match
  '/api/internalized/users', // must NOT match — prefix collision check
];
const pattern = /^\/api\/internal(\/.*)?$/;
paths.forEach(p =>
  console.log(p, pattern.test(p) ? '✅ matched' : '❌ skipped'),
);
```

---

## Principle

> **Middleware is only as reliable as its entry point contract.**  
> A proxy helper module (`proxy.ts`) has zero effect unless explicitly called from the one file Next.js owns: `middleware.ts` at the project root. Treat the matcher as a typed contract — validate it against a known URL matrix on every framework upgrade, because wildcard semantics are version-sensitive (AP-072). Add a runtime path guard inside the proxy function itself as defence-in-depth so a misconfigured matcher degrades to a no-op rather than a security bypass.
